Now I can see the problem clearly. Look at lines 459-460 and line 480 in `QuartzSchedulerThread.cs`:

```csharp
// Line 459-460: Initialize the shell on the calling thread (which is the QuartzSchedulerThread)
shell = qsRsrcs.JobRunShellFactory.CreateJobRunShell(bndle);
await shell.Initialize(qs, CancellationToken.None).ConfigureAwait(false);  // <-- NewJob called here, AsyncLocal set

// Line 480: Run the shell on a different thread from the thread pool
var threadPoolRunResult = qsRsrcs.ThreadPool.RunInThread(() => shell.Run(CancellationToken.None));  // <-- Execute called on different thread
```

The `Initialize` call (which calls `IJobFactory.NewJob`) happens on the QuartzSchedulerThread's execution context. But then `shell.Run` is dispatched to a thread pool thread. Since `AsyncLocal<T>` values flow with `ExecutionContext` across async/await but NOT across explicit thread switching (like `RunInThread` which likely uses `Task.Run` or similar), the `AsyncLocal` values set during `NewJob` are lost when the job executes on a different thread.

Now let me look at how the thread pool works and the `IJobFactory` interface.

