Let me look more carefully at the issue. I think the problem might be in `TaskSchedulingThreadPool.RunInThread` and how it creates the task. Let me check the `new Task<Task>(runnable)` behavior with `ExecutionContext`.

Actually wait - I just realized something. The `runnable` lambda I'm passing is:
```csharp
async () =>
{
    await shell.Initialize(qs, CancellationToken.None).ConfigureAwait(false);
    ...
    await shell.Run(CancellationToken.None).ConfigureAwait(false);
}
```

This lambda is passed to `RunInThread`, which does:
```csharp
var task = new Task<Task>(runnable);
task.Start(Scheduler);
```

The `new Task<Task>(runnable)` captures the `ExecutionContext` at the point of creation (in `QuartzSchedulerThread.Run()`). This `ExecutionContext` doesn't have `CurrentTenant` set. Then `task.Start(Scheduler)` runs the task on the thread pool, restoring the captured `ExecutionContext`. Inside the lambda, `Initialize` sets `CurrentTenant.Value`. But then...

Wait, the `ExecutionContext` is captured at task creation time and restored before the lambda runs. When the lambda runs and `Initialize` sets `CurrentTenant.Value = "Tenant-123"`, this modifies the `ExecutionContext`. Then when the lambda continues after `await`, the `ExecutionContext` flows with the continuation. This should work.

